# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-cloudfront-functions
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/amazon-cloudfront] CloudFront has servers located in the United Kingdom, Ireland, the Netherlands, Germany, Spain, Hong Kong, Singapore, Japan, Taiwan, Vietnam, Indonesia, India, Australia, South America, Africa, and several major cities in the United States.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/amazon-cloudfront] In May 2025, the service operated from 1600+ edge locations on every continent excluding Antarctica.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/amazon-cloudfront] CloudFront operates on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/amazon-cloudfront] CloudFront competes with larger CDNs, such as Akamai, Azion, and Cloudflare.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/amazon-cloudfront] Upon launch, Larry Dignan of ZDNet News stated that CloudFront could cause price and margin reductions for competing CDNs.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] A **content delivery network** (**CDN**) or **content distribution network** is a geographically distributed network of proxy servers and corresponding data centers.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] CDNs provide high availability and performance ("speed") through geographical distribution relative to end users, and arose in the late 1990s to alleviate the performance bottlenecks of the Internet as it was becoming a critical medium.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Since then, CDNs have grown to serve a large portion of Internet content, including text, graphics and scripts, downloadable objects (media files, software, and documents), applications (e-commerce, portals), live streaming media, on-demand streaming media, and social media services.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] CDNs are a layer in the internet ecosystem.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Content owners such as media companies and e-commerce vendors pay CDN operators to deliver their content to their end users.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] In turn, a CDN pays Internet service providers (ISPs), carriers, and network operators for hosting its servers in their data centers.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] CDN vendors may cross over into other industries like security, DDoS protection and web application firewalls (WAF), and WAN optimization.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Content delivery service providers include Akamai Technologies, Cloudflare, Amazon CloudFront, Qwilt (Cisco), Fastly, CDN77, BunnyCDN, EdgeNext, and Google Cloud CDN.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] CDN nodes are usually deployed in multiple locations, often over multiple Internet backbones.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Benefits include reducing bandwidth costs, improving page load times, and increasing the global availability of content.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] The number of nodes and servers making up a CDN varies, depending on the architecture, some reaching thousands of nodes with tens of thousands of servers on many remote points of presence (PoPs).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Others build a global network and have a small number of geographical PoPs.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Requests for content are typically algorithmically directed to nodes that are optimal in some way.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for performance, locations that are best for serving content to the user may be chosen.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] This may be measured by choosing locations that are the fewest hops or the shortest time to the requesting client, or the highest server performance, to optimize delivery across local networks.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for cost, locations that are the least expensive may be chosen instead.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] In an optimal scenario, these two goals tend to align, as **edge servers** that are close to the end user at the edge of the network may have an advantage in performance and cost.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Most CDN providers will provide their services over a varying, defined, set of PoPs, depending on the coverage desired, such as United States, Asia-Pacific, International or Global, etc.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] These sets of PoPs can be called "edges", "edge nodes", "edge servers", or "edge networks" as they would be the closest edge of CDN assets to the end user.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] CDN providers profit either from direct fees paid by content providers using their network, or profit from the user analytics and tracking data collected as their scripts are being loaded onto customers' websites inside their browser origin.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] As such these services are being pointed out as potential privacy intrusions for the purpose of behavioral targeting and solutions are being created to restore single-origin serving and caching of resources.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] In particular, a website using a CDN may violate the EU's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] For example, in 2021 a German court forbade the use of a CDN on a university website, because this caused the transmission of the user's IP address to the CDN, which violated the GDPR.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] CDNs serving JavaScript have also been targeted as a way to inject malicious content into pages using them.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Subresource Integrity mechanism was created in response to ensure that the page loads a script whose content is known and constrained to a hash referenced by the website author.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] The Internet was designed according to the end-to-end principle.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] This principle keeps the core network relatively simple and moves the intelligence as much as possible to the network end-points: the hosts and clients.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] As a result, the core network is specialized, optimized, and simplified to only forward data packets.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Content Delivery Networks extend the transport network by distributing on it a variety of intelligent applications employing techniques designed to optimize content delivery.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] The resulting tightly integrated overlay uses web caching, server-load balancing, request routing, and content services.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Web caches store popular content on servers that have the greatest demand for the content requested.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] These shared network appliances reduce bandwidth requirements, reduce server load, and improve the client response times for content stored in the cache.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Web caches are populated based on requests from users (pull caching) or based on preloaded content disseminated from content servers (push caching).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Server-load balancing uses one or more techniques including service-based (global load balancing) or hardware-based (i.e. layer 4–7 switches, also known as a web switch, content switch, or multilayer switch) to share traffic among a number of servers or web caches.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Here the switch is assigned a single virtual IP address.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Traffic arriving at the switch is then directed to one of the real web servers attached to the switch.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] This has the advantage of balancing load, increasing total capacity, improving scalability, and providing increased reliability by redistributing the load of a failed web server and providing server health checks.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] A content cluster or service node can be formed using a layer 4–7 switch to balance load across a number of servers or a number of web caches within the network.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Request routing directs client requests to the content source best able to serve the request.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] This may involve directing a client request to the service node that is closest to the client, or to the one with the most capacity.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] A variety of algorithms are used to route the request.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] These include Global Server Load Balancing, DNS-based request routing, Dynamic metafile generation, HTML rewriting, and anycasting.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Proximity—choosing the closest service node—is estimated using a variety of techniques including reactive probing, proactive probing, and connection monitoring.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] CDNs use a variety of methods of content delivery including, but not limited to, manual asset copying, active web caches, and global hardware load balancers.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Several protocol suites are designed to provide access to a wide variety of content services distributed throughout a content network.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] The Internet Content Adaptation Protocol (ICAP) was developed in the late 1990s to provide an open standard for connecting application servers.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] A more recently defined and robust solution is provided by the Open Pluggable Edge Services (OPES) protocol.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] This architecture defines OPES service applications that can reside on the OPES processor itself or be executed remotely on a Callout Server.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Edge Side Includes or ESI is a small markup language for edge-level dynamic web content assembly.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] It is fairly common for websites to have generated content.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] It could be because of changing content like catalogs or forums, or because of the personalization.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] This creates a problem for caching systems.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] To overcome this problem, a group of companies created ESI.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] In *peer-to-peer (P2P)* content-delivery networks, clients provide resources as well as use them.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] This means that, unlike client–server systems, the content-centric networks can actually perform better as more users begin to access the content (especially with protocols such as Bittorrent that require users to share).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] This property is one of the major advantages of using P2P networks because it makes the setup and running costs very small for the original content distributor.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] To incentive peers to participate in the P2P network, web3 and blockchain technologies can be used: participating nodes receive crypto tokens in exchange of their involvement.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] If content owners are not satisfied with the options or costs of a commercial CDN service, they can create their own CDN.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] A private CDN consists of PoPs (points of presence) that are only serving content for their owner.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] These PoPs can be caching servers, reverse proxies or application delivery controllers.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] It can be as simple as two caching servers, or large enough to serve petabytes of content.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] When a private CDN is deployed within a company network, it is also referred as Entreprise CDN or **eCDN**.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Large content distribution networks may even build and set up their own private network to distribute copies of content across cache locations.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Such private networks are usually used in conjunction with public networks as a backup option in case the capacity of the private network is not enough or there is a failure which leads to capacity reduction.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Since the same content has to be distributed across many locations, a variety of multicasting techniques may be used to reduce bandwidth consumption.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Over private networks, it has also been proposed to select multicast trees according to network load conditions to more efficiently utilize available network capacity.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] The rapid growth of streaming video traffic required large capital expenditures by broadband providers in order to meet this demand and retain subscribers by delivering a sufficiently good quality of experience.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] To address this, telecommunications service providers have begun to launch their own content delivery networks as a means to lessen the demands on the network backbone and reduce infrastructure investments.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Because they own the networks over which video content is transmitted, telco CDNs have advantages over traditional CDNs.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] They own the last mile and can deliver content closer to the end-user because it can be cached deep in their networks.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] This deep caching minimizes the distance that video data travels over the general Internet and delivers it more quickly and reliably.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Telco CDNs also have a built-in cost advantage since traditional CDNs must lease bandwidth from them and build the operator's margin into their own cost model.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] In addition, by operating their own content delivery infrastructure, telco operators have better control over the utilization of their resources.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Content management operations performed by CDNs are usually applied without (or with very limited) information about the network (e.g., topology, utilization etc.) of the telco-operators with which they interact or have business relationships.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] These pose a number of challenges for the telco-operators who have a limited sphere of action in face of the impact of these operations on the utilization of their resources.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] In contrast, the deployment of telco-CDNs allows operators to implement their own content management operations, which enables them to have a better control over the utilization of their resources and, as such, provide better quality of service and experience to their end users.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] In June 2011, StreamingMedia.com reported that a group of TSPs had founded an Operator Carrier Exchange (OCX) to interconnect their networks and compete more directly against large traditional CDNs like Akamai and Limelight Networks, which have extensive PoPs worldwide.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] This way, telcos are building a Federated CDN offering, which is more interesting for a content provider willing to deliver its content to the aggregated audience of this federation.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] It is likely that in a near future, other telco CDN federations will be created.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] They will grow by enrollment of new telcos joining the federation and bringing network presence and their Internet subscriber bases to the existing ones.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] The Open Caching specification by Streaming Video Technology Alliance defines a set of APIs that allows a Content Provider to deliver its content using several CDNs in a consistent way, seeing each CDN provider the same way through these APIs.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Combining several CDN services allow Content Providers to not rely on a single CDN service, especially concerned to deal with high peak audience during live events.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] There are several ways to allocate traffic to a particular CDN among the list, either client-side CDN selection, or server-side (at the Content Provider's origin) or cloud-side (in the middle, between the content origin and the audience).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] CDN selection criteria can be performance, availability and cost.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Traditionally, CDNs have used the IP of the client's recursive DNS resolver to geo-locate the client.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] While this is a sound approach in many situations, this leads to poor client performance if the client uses a non-local recursive DNS resolver that is far away.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] For instance, a CDN may route requests from a client in India to its edge server in Singapore, if that client uses a public DNS resolver in Singapore, causing poor performance for that client.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Indeed, a recent study showed that in many countries where public DNS resolvers are in popular use, the median distance between the clients and their recursive DNS resolvers can be as high as a thousand miles.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] In August 2011, a global consortium of leading Internet service providers led by Google announced their official implementation of the edns-client-subnet IETF Internet Draft, which is intended to accurately localize DNS resolution responses.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] The initiative involves a limited number of leading DNS service providers, such as Google Public DNS, and CDN service providers as well.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] With the edns-client-subnet EDNS0 option, CDNs can now utilize the IP address of the requesting client's subnet when resolving DNS requests.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] This approach, called end-user mapping, has been adopted by CDNs and it has been shown to drastically reduce the round-trip latencies and improve performance for clients who use public DNS or other non-local resolvers.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] However, the use of EDNS0 also has drawbacks as it decreases the effectiveness of caching resolutions at the recursive resolvers, increases the total DNS resolution traffic, and raises a privacy concern of exposing the client's subnet.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Virtualization technologies are being used to deploy virtual CDNs (vCDNs) (also known as a software-defined CDN or sd-CDN) with the goal to reduce content provider costs, and at the same time, increase elasticity and decrease service delay.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] With vCDNs, it is possible to avoid traditional CDN limitations, such as performance, reliability and availability since virtual caches are deployed dynamically (as virtual machines or containers) in physical servers distributed across the provider's geographical coverage.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] As the virtual cache placement is based on both the content type and server or end-user geographic location, the vCDNs have a significant impact on service delivery and network congestion.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] To boost performance, delivery to clients from servers can use alternate non-HTTP protocols such as WebRTC and WebSockets.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] In 2017, Addy Osmani of Google started referring to software solutions that could integrate naturally with the Responsive Web Design paradigm (with particular reference to the <picture> element) as **Image CDN**s.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] The expression referred to the ability of a web architecture to serve multiple versions of the same image through HTTP, depending on the properties of the browser requesting it, as determined by either the browser or the server-side logic.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] The purpose of Image CDNs was, in Google's vision, to serve high-quality images (or, better, images perceived as high-quality by the human eye) while preserving download speed, thus contributing to a great User experience (UX).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Arguably, the *Image CDN* term was originally a misnomer, as neither Cloudinary nor Imgix (the examples quoted by Google in the 2017 guide by Addy Osmani) were, at the time, a CDN in the classical sense of the term.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Shortly afterwards, though, several companies offered solutions that allowed developers to serve different versions of their graphical assets according to several strategies.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] Many of these solutions were built on top of traditional CDNs, such as Akamai, CloudFront, Fastly, Edgecast and Cloudflare.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/content-delivery-network] At the same time, other solutions that already provided an image multi-serving service joined the Image CDN definition by either offering CDN functionality natively (ImageEngine) or integrating with one of the existing CDNs (Cloudinary/Akamai, Imgix/Fastly).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] The term began being used in the 1990s to describe content delivery networks—these were used to deliver website and video content from servers located near users.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] In the early 2000s, these systems expanded their scope to hosting other applications, leading to early edge computing services.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] These services could do things like find dealers, manage shopping carts, gather real-time data, and place ads.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] The Internet of things (IoT), where devices are connected to the Internet, is often linked with edge computing.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Edge computing involves running computer programs that deliver quick responses close to where requests are made.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Karim Arabi, during an IEEE DAC 2014 keynote and later at an MIT MTL Seminar in 2015, described edge computing as computing that occurs outside the cloud, at the network's edge, particularly for applications needing immediate data processing.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Edge computing is often equated with fog computing, particularly in smaller setups.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] However, in larger deployments, such as smart cities, fog computing serves as a distinct layer between edge computing and cloud computing, with each layer having its own responsibilities.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] "The State of the Edge" report explains that edge computing focuses on servers located close to the end-users.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Alex Reznik, Chair of the ETSI MEC ISG standards committee, defines 'edge' loosely as anything that's not a traditional data center.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] In cloud gaming, edge nodes, known as "gamelets", are typically within one or two network hops from the client, ensuring quick response times for real-time games.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Edge computing might use virtualization technology to simplify deploying and managing various applications on edge servers.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] In 2018, the world's data was expected to grow 61 percent to 175 zettabytes by 2025.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] According to research firm Gartner, around 10 percent of enterprise-generated data is created and processed outside a traditional centralized data center or cloud.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] By 2025, the firm predicts that this figure will reach 75 percent.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] The increase in IoT devices at the edge of the network is producing a massive amount of data — storing and using all that data in cloud data centers pushes network bandwidth requirements to the limit.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Despite the improvements in network technology, data centers cannot guarantee acceptable transfer rates and response times, which often is a critical requirement for many applications.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Furthermore, devices at the edge constantly consume data coming from the cloud, forcing companies to decentralize data storage and service provisioning, leveraging physical proximity to the end user.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] In a similar way, the aim of edge computing is to move the computation away from data centers towards the edge of the network, exploiting smart objects, mobile phones, or network gateways to perform tasks and provide services on behalf of the cloud.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] By moving services to the edge, it is possible to provide content caching, service delivery, persistent data storage, and IoT management resulting in better response times and transfer rates.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] At the same time, distributing the logic to different network nodes introduces new issues and challenges.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] The distributed nature of this paradigm introduces a shift in security schemes used in cloud computing.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] In edge computing, data may travel between different distributed nodes connected via the internet, and thus requires special encryption mechanisms independent of the cloud.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] This approach minimizes latency, reduces bandwidth consumption, and enhances real-time responsiveness for applications.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Edge nodes may also be resource-constrained devices, limiting the choice in terms of security methods.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Moreover, a shift from centralized top-down infrastructure to a decentralized trust model is required.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] On the other hand, by keeping and processing data at the edge, it is possible to increase privacy by minimizing the transmission of sensitive information to the cloud.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Furthermore, the ownership of collected data shifts from service providers to end-users.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Scalability in a distributed network must face different issues.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] First, it must take into account the heterogeneity of the devices, having different performance and energy constraints, the highly dynamic condition, and the reliability of the connections compared to more robust infrastructure of cloud data centers.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Moreover, security requirements may introduce further latency in the communication between nodes, which may slow down the scaling process.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] The state-of-the-art scheduling technique can increase the effective utilization of edge resources and scales the edge server by assigning minimum edge resources to each offloaded task.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Management of failovers is crucial in order to keep a service alive.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] If a single node goes down and is unreachable, users should still be able to access a service without interruptions.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Moreover, edge computing systems must provide actions to recover from a failure and alert the user about the incident.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] To this aim, each device must maintain the network topology of the entire distributed system, so that detection of errors and recovery become easily applicable.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Other factors that may influence this aspect are the connection technologies in use, which may provide different levels of reliability, and the accuracy of the data produced at the edge that could be unreliable due to particular environment conditions.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] As an example, an edge computing device, such as a voice assistant, may continue to provide service to local users even during cloud service or internet outages.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Edge computing brings analytical computational resources close to the end users and therefore can increase the responsiveness and throughput of applications.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] A well-designed edge platform would significantly outperform a traditional cloud-based system.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Some applications rely on short response times, making edge computing a significantly more feasible option than cloud computing.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Examples range from IoT to autonomous driving, anything health or human / public safety relevant, or involving human perception such as facial recognition, which typically takes a human between 370-620 ms to perform.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Edge computing is more likely to be able to mimic the same perception speed as humans, which is useful in applications such as augmented reality, where the headset should preferably recognize who a person is at the same time as the wearer does.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Due to the nearness of the analytical resources to the end users, sophisticated analytical tools and artificial intelligence tools can run on the edge of the system.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] This placement at the edge helps to increase operational efficiency and is responsible for many advantages to the system.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] In distributed AI systems on the edge, data compression is increasingly recognized as a foundational design layer to mitigate bandwidth constraints caused by the exchange of large models and high-resolution sensor streams.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] By using servers located on a local edge network to perform those computations, the video files only need to be transmitted in the local network.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Avoiding transmission over the internet results in significant bandwidth savings and therefore increases efficiency.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] If the recognition is performed locally, it is possible to send the recognized text to the cloud rather than audio recordings, significantly reducing the amount of required bandwidth.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Edge application services reduce the volumes of data that must be moved, the consequent traffic, and the distance that data must travel.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] That provides lower latency and reduces transmission costs.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Computation offloading for real-time applications, such as facial recognition algorithms, showed considerable improvements in response times, as demonstrated in early research.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Further research showed that using resource-rich machines called cloudlets or micro data centers near mobile users, which offer services typically found in the cloud, provided improvements in execution time when some of the tasks are offloaded to the edge node.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] On the other hand, offloading every task may result in a slowdown due to transfer times between device and nodes, so depending on the workload, an optimal configuration can be defined.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] An IoT-based power grid system enables communication of electricity and data to monitor and control the power grid, which makes energy management more efficient.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] Other notable applications include connected cars, self-driving cars, smart cities, Industry 4.0, home automation, missiles,, satellite systems , as well as frameworks such as MediaPipe.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/edge-computing] The growing field of **edge artificial intelligence** (edge AI or edge intelligence, sometimes referred to as "local AI" or "on-device AI") implements artificial intelligence in an edge computing environment, on the device or close to where data is collected.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Here is an example of JavaScript syntax.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Latency is physically a consequence of the limited velocity at which any physical interaction can propagate.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] The magnitude of this velocity is always less than or equal to the speed of light.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Therefore, every physical system with any physical separation (distance) between cause and effect will experience some sort of latency, regardless of the nature of the stimulation to which it has been exposed.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] The precise definition of latency depends on the system being observed or the nature of the simulation.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] In communications, the lower limit of latency is determined by the medium being used to transfer information.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] In reliable two-way communication systems, latency limits the maximum rate at which information can be transmitted, as there is often a limit on the amount of information that is in-flight at any given moment.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Perceptible latency has a strong effect on user satisfaction and usability in the field of human–machine interaction.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Online games are sensitive to latency (lag), since fast response times to new events occurring during a game session are rewarded while slow response times may carry penalties.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Due to a delay in transmission of game events, a player with a high-latency internet connection may show slow responses in spite of appropriate reaction time.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] This gives players with low-latency connections a technical advantage.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Trading using computers has developed to the point where millisecond improvements in network speeds offer a competitive advantage for financial institutions.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] However, in a non-trivial network, a typical packet will be forwarded over multiple links and gateways, each of which will not begin to forward the packet until it has been completely received.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] In such a network, the minimal latency is the sum of the transmission delay of each link, plus the forwarding latency of each gateway.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] In practice, minimal latency also includes queuing and processing delays.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Queuing delay occurs when a gateway receives multiple packets from different sources heading toward the same destination.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Since typically only one packet can be transmitted at a time, some of the packets must queue for transmission, incurring additional delay.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Processing delays are incurred while a gateway determines what to do with a newly received packet.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Bufferbloat can also cause increased latency that is an order of magnitude or more.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] The combination of propagation, serialization, queuing, and processing delays often produces a complex and variable network latency profile.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Latency limits total throughput in reliable two-way communication systems as described by the bandwidth-delay product.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Latency in optical fiber is largely a function of the speed of light.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] This would equate to a latency of 3.33 μs for every kilometer of path length.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] The index of refraction of most fiber optic cables is about 1.5, meaning that light travels about 1.5 times as fast in a vacuum as it does in the cable.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] This works out to about 5.0 μs of latency for every kilometer.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] In shorter metro networks, higher latency can be experienced due to extra distance in building risers and cross-connects.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] To calculate the latency of a connection, one has to know the distance traveled by the fiber, which is rarely a straight line, since it has to traverse geographic contours and obstacles, such as roads and railway tracks, as well as other rights-of-way.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Due to imperfections in the fiber, light degrades as it is transmitted through it.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] For distances of greater than 100 kilometers, amplifiers or regenerators are deployed.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Latency introduced by these components needs to be taken into account.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Low Earth orbit is sometimes used to cut this delay, at the expense of more complicated satellite tracking on the ground and requiring more satellites in the satellite constellation to ensure continuous coverage.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Audio latency is the delay between when an audio signal enters and when it emerges from a system.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Potential contributors to latency in an audio system include analog-to-digital conversion, buffering, digital signal processing, transmission time, digital-to-analog conversion and the speed of sound in air.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Video latency refers to the degree of delay between the time a transfer of a video stream is requested and the actual time that transfer begins.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Networks that exhibit relatively small delays are known as low-latency networks, while their counterparts are known as high-latency networks.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Any individual workflow within a system of workflows can be subject to some type of operational latency.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] It may even be the case that an individual system may have more than one type of latency, depending on the type of participant or goal-seeking behavior.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] This is best illustrated by the following two examples involving air travel.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] From the point of view of a passenger, latency can be described as follows.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Suppose John Doe flies from London to New York.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] The latency of his trip is the time it takes him to go from his house in England to the hotel he is staying at in New York.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] This is independent of the throughput of the London-New York air link, whether there were 100 passengers a day making the trip or 10000, the latency of the trip would remain the same.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] From the point of view of flight operations personnel, latency can be entirely different.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Consider the staff at the London and New York airports.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Only a limited number of planes are able to make the transatlantic journey, so when one lands, they must prepare it for the return trip as quickly as possible.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] However, cleaning, refueling and loading the cargo can be done at the same time.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Passengers can only be loaded after cleaning is complete.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] The people involved in the turnaround are interested only in the time it takes for their individual tasks.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] When all of the tasks are done at the same time, however, it is possible to reduce the latency to the length of the longest task.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] If some steps have prerequisites, it becomes more difficult to perform all steps in parallel.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] In the example above, the requirement to clean the plane before loading passengers results in a minimum latency longer than any single task.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Any mechanical process encounters limitations modeled by Newtonian physics.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] The behavior of disk drives provides an example of mechanical latency.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Here, it is the time seek time for the actuator arm to be positioned above the appropriate track and then rotational latency for the data encoded on a platter to rotate from its current position to a position under the disk read-and-write head.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Computers run instructions in the context of a process.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] In the context of computer multitasking, the execution of the process can be postponed if other processes are also executing.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] In addition, the operating system can schedule when to perform the action that the process is commanding.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] For example, suppose a process commands that a computer card's voltage output be set high-low-high-low and so on at a rate of 1000 Hz.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] The operating system schedules the process for each transition (high-low or low-high) based on a hardware clock, such as the High Precision Event Timer.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] The latency is the delay between the events generated by the hardware clock and the actual transitions of voltage from high to low or low to high.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Many desktop operating systems have performance limitations that create additional latency.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] The problem may be mitigated with real-time extensions and patches such as PREEMPT RT.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] On embedded systems, the real-time execution of instructions is often supported by a real-time operating system.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Note that in software systems, benchmarking against *average* and *median* latency can be misleading because a few outliers can distort them.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Instead, software architects and software developers should use "99th percentile".
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] In simulation applications, latency refers to the time delay, often measured in milliseconds, between initial input and output clearly discernible to the simulator trainee or simulator subject.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Latency is sometimes also called *transport delay*.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] Some authorities distinguish between latency and transport delay by using the term *latency* in the sense of the extra time delay of a system over and above the reaction time of the vehicle being simulated, but this requires detailed knowledge of the vehicle dynamics and can be controversial.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] In simulators with both visual and motion systems, it is particularly important that the latency of the motion system not be greater than of the visual system, or symptoms of simulator sickness may result.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] This is because, in the real world, motion cues are those of acceleration and are quickly transmitted to the brain, typically in less than 50 milliseconds; this is followed some milliseconds later by a perception of change in the visual scene.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] The visual scene change is essentially one of change of perspective or displacement of objects, such as the horizon, which takes some time to build up to discernible amounts after the initial acceleration that caused the displacement.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/latency-engineering] A simulator should, therefore, reflect the real-world situation by ensuring that the motion latency is equal to or less than that of the visual system and not the other way round.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:aws-cloudfront-functions/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
